nl.tudelft.simulation.dsol.simulators

Class DEVSSimulator<A extends java.lang.Comparable<A>,R extends java.lang.Number & java.lang.Comparable<R>,T extends SimTime<A,R,T>>

  • java.lang.Object
    • nl.tudelft.simulation.event.EventProducer
      • nl.tudelft.simulation.dsol.simulators.Simulator<A,R,T>
        • nl.tudelft.simulation.dsol.simulators.DEVSSimulator<A,R,T>
  • Type Parameters:
    A - the absolute storage type for the simulation time, e.g. Calendar, Duration, or Double.
    R - the relative type for time storage, e.g. Long for the Calendar. For most non-calendar types, such as Double or Long, the absolute and relative types are the same.
    T - the simulation time type based on the absolute and relative time.
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Runnable, java.rmi.Remote, DEVSSimulatorInterface<A,R,T>, SimulatorInterface<A,R,T>, nl.tudelft.simulation.event.EventProducerInterface
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    DEVDESSSimulator, DEVSAnimator, DEVSSimulator.CalendarDouble, DEVSSimulator.CalendarFloat, DEVSSimulator.CalendarLong, DEVSSimulator.TimeDouble, DEVSSimulator.TimeDoubleUnit, DEVSSimulator.TimeFloat, DEVSSimulator.TimeFloatUnit, DEVSSimulator.TimeLong

    public class DEVSSimulator<A extends java.lang.Comparable<A>,R extends java.lang.Number & java.lang.Comparable<R>,T extends SimTime<A,R,T>>
extends Simulator<A,R,T>
implements DEVSSimulatorInterface<A,R,T>
    The DEVS defines the interface of the DEVS simulator. DEVS stands for the Discrete Event System Specification. More information on Discrete Event Simulation can be found in "Theory of Modeling and Simulation" by Bernard Zeigler et. al.

      • run

        public void run()
        The run method defines the actual time step mechanism of the simulator. The implementation of this method depends on the formalism. Where discrete event formalisms loop over an eventlist continuous simulators take pre-defined time steps.
        Specified by:
        run in interface java.lang.Runnable
